               <p>237. <persName id="def1-237-18421128" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-237-18421128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-237-18421128" type="age" value="56"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-237-18421128" type="surname" value="MORRISS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-237-18421128" type="given" value="THOMAS HAMER"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS HAMER MORRISS</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-237-18421128" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-237-18421128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-237-18421128" type="age" value="54"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-237-18421128" type="surname" value="HORNER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-237-18421128" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN HORNER</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18421128-237-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18421128-237-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18421128-237-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp>were in<lb></lb>dicted for a misdemeanor.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1239" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1239" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1239" type="surname" value="CRAWFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1239" type="given" value="FANNY"></interp>FANNY CRAWFORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Victor Dumar, an importer and dealer in French shoes, in Regent-street. On the 23rd of Sept. a person named William Clark called, and asked me to show him some French goods—I asked if it was for wholesale or retail, he said wholesale that he was living at Epsom, and had a large shop there—he had dealt in English shoes, but his customers had wanted French goods, and he came in, seeing Mr. Dumar's name on the door—he said he should require 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth, as a sample of each sort—he said, "What are Mr. Dumar's terms?"—I said, "Ready money, with two and a half discount, or three months' credit; we must have a refer<lb></lb>ence, if we give credit"—he said, "I can give you a very good reference, one that I am sure you will be satisfied with"—he then handed me a bill, with "Thomas Hamer, 20, Bread-street-hill" on it—he requested that Mr. Durnar would go on the following morning, before eleven o'clock, for the reference, as Mr. Hamer was then most likely to be in the way—on the next day I went to No. 20, Bread-street-hill—I asked for Mr. Hamer, and the prisoner Morris said, "I am Mr. Hamer"—I saw the name of Thomas Hamer on the side of the door—I said Mr. William Clark, of Epsom, had referred Mr. Dumar to him, as to his capability of paying for goods—he said, "Yes, I know Mr. Clark very well indeed"—he said that he had served him with goods ever since he had opened his shop, and had always found him very punctual in his payments, his bills were always taken np before they were due, at the end of six weeks or two months—he said, "What kind of goods are they?"—I said, "French boots and shoes"—he said, "Of course they are of the first quality; because I know that Clark's customers are all gentlefolks; there are a great many gentlemen's seats about Epsom, which of course you are aware of"—I asked if we could give credit with propriety—he said, "Cer<lb></lb>tainly, without the slightest danger"—I said, "Has he been established long"—he said, "Somewhere about three years"—there was a counting-house and a warehouse—I did not look further—I thought, from the appearance, he was a very extensive merchant—when I went back, on the same day, Clark called again—he said, "Have you called on Mr. Hamer this morning?" I said, "Yes, I called on him, and Mr. Dunn was perfectly satisfied with the character he has given you"—before he went away he had eighteen pairs</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184211280163"></xptr>
               <p>of shoes—he said he was in want of them, as he had received an order, and on the Monday or Tuesday he called with a horse and cart, and took away the remainder, amounting to 37<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I cautioned him about the danger of French goods being exposed to the weather—he said "Oh, I have pro<lb></lb>vided against that, I have a very large glass case"—I said if not, they would be soiled—he promised to call in a week and pay 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I have never seen the 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I was present when he gave a bill for 27<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I saw him write the bill—I believe. these papers to be his handwriting.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1240" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1240" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1240" type="surname" value="DUMAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1240" type="given" value="VICTOR"></interp>VICTOR DUMAR</persName>
                  </hi>. Crawford was in my service—I have never received payment for these boots and shoes from Mr. Clark or Hamer—I went down to Epsom—I found no shop with a handsome glass case.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1241" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1241" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1241" type="surname" value="PETCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1241" type="given" value="JOSEPH ELSWORTH"></interp>JOSEPH ELSWORTH PETCH</persName>
                  </hi>. About the 21st of Oct. I saw a person who said his name was William Clark—he said he was residing at Epsom, and he wanted some boots—he referred me to Mr. Hamer, of Bread-street-hill—I went there, and saw Morris—he said, "My name is Hamer"—Clark had said he was about to open a shop, and Morris said he was about to supply him with 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of goods; he knew his family, and knew him to be a respectable man—I asked as to his honesty and Industry—he gave him a very excellent character—Clark obtained from me goods to the amount of 24<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. odd—he paid me 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>—the term I bad proposed was half cash—he took away my goods in a cart on the 28th of Oct.—I have never seen him since—if the reference had not been satisfactory I certainly should not have parted with my goods—the premises of Hamer were well stocked with crates and other merchandise.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1242" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1242" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1242" type="surname" value="PIPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1242" type="given" value="THOMAS FOOT"></interp>THOMAS FOOT PIPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a stay-maker. On the 27th of Oct. William Clark came to me—he said be lived at Epsom, and wanted some goods—I required a reference—he gave me one to Thomas Hamer, Bread-street-hill—I sent my clerk there, and from his representation I ultimately parted with some goods—I have not seen Clark since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1243" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1243" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1243" type="surname" value="KNIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1243" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KNIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Piper. I went by his direction to No. 20, Bread-street-hill—I inquired for Mr. Hamer—Morris came forward and said his name was Hamer—I told him I came to inquire the character of William Clark, of Epsom—he said, "I know Mr. Clark very well, walk into my counting-house"—he gave him an excellent character, said he knew his family, and he had no doubt we should be very safe in giving him credit—he said he thought we were perfectly safe in trusting him—at that time there were goods strewed about the warehouse in large quantities—I thought it had the appearance of a place of large business.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1244" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1244" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1244" type="surname" value="SWIFT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1244" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SWIFT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a boot-maker, and live in Greville-street, Hatton<lb></lb>garden. On the 1st of November Clark called on me, and said his name was William Clark, of High-street, Epsom, and he wanted a quantity of boots and shbes, about 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth—he referred me to Mr. Hamer, of Bread-street-hill—I sent my clerk there, and after a report from him I delivered to Clark goods to the amount of 39<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. with a bill of the goods, charging the ham<lb></lb>per 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., if not returned—Clark came with a horse and cart, and took them away—I went afterwards with an officer to Hamer's place—we went right through the house—we found several crates stuffed with straw, which were tied down, having the appearance of being full—some of the crates in the bottom warehouse had a few dishes and plates strewed at the top of them, but nothing under them but straw—we found several books, but no entry, except an old one of Jones Lloyd and Co., in 1821.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe you received some money on account? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—we found a desk at Hamer's—I think it was shut when we went in, but we opened it—it was not locked. <persName id="t18421128-name-1245" type="witnessName">
                     <interp inst="t18421128-name-1245" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18421128-name-1245" type="surname" value="SADD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18421128-name-1245" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">WILLIAM SADD</hi>
                  </persName>. I am clerk to Mr. Swift. I went to Bread-street-hill, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184211280164"></xptr>
               <p>saw Morris—he said his name was Hamer—I told him what I came about—he said he had known Mr. Clark some time, that he was a highly respectable man, and we might trust him to twice the amount of goods he had asked us for.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1246" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1246" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1246" type="surname" value="HOLLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1246" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOLLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an occasional customer of Mr. Swift. I know his boots—some of them were exhibited to me for sale, on the 8th of Nov., by a person named Davis—I let it out that I knew Mr. Swift, and I made an ap<lb></lb>pointment for the purchase of the goods—I went to the house where Davis had shown me the goods—he was gone, and they knew nothing about it—I had actually seen some of these same goods in Swift's warehouse—I commu<lb></lb>nicated this to Mr. Swift.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1247" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1247" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1247" type="surname" value="MATSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1247" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY MATSON</persName>
                  </hi>. Mr. Dumar lodges with me, I was going into the City, and proffered my assistance—I went, at his request, to No. 20, Bread-street-hill, and took this bill with me—(<hi rend="italic">looking at a bill</hi>)—I saw Homer—I said I was about to take the bill; I wished to know if Clark was a responsible man—he said he was in business in Epsom, he knew him to be a very respectable man, and I need have no fear—he said Hamer was not at home, but he would be in shortly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1248" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1248" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1248" type="surname" value="SWIFT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1248" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SWIFT</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I went subsequently to the warehouse in Bread-street-hill, and saw Homer—he said he was clerk to Mr. Hamor—I asked him Mr. Hamer's private address—he said he did not know it, he had only been with him seven weeks—he was in a situation in which he might have become acquainted with the crates that were there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1249" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1249" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
